'''St Mary's Church, Ellesmere''', stands on a hill in the town of [[Ellesmere, Shropshire|Ellesmere]], [[Shropshire]], England.  It is an active [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] [[parish church]] in the deanery of Ellesmere, the archdeaconry of Salop, and the [[diocese of Hereford]].<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.achurchnearyou.com/ellesmere-st-mary/| title = Ellesmere The Blessed Virgin Mary, Ellesmere| accessdate =14 February 2013| publisher = [[Church of England]]}}</ref>  The church is designated by [[English Heritage]] as a Grade&nbsp;I [[listed building]].<ref name=nhl>{{NHLE |num= 1055505|desc= Church of St Mary, Ellesmere Urban|accessdate= 14 February 2013|separator=,|ps=}}</ref>

==History==

The church originated in the [[Norman conquest of England|Norman era]], and still contains some elements of [[Norman architecture]].  The south [[chancel]] chapel dates from the early 14th&nbsp;century, and the tower from between 1439 and 1449.  In 1848<U+2013>49 the church was altered and [[Victorian restoration|restored]] by [[George Gilbert Scott]]. His work included replacing the [[nave]], restoring the [[transept]]s, and adding a stair [[turret]] to the south transept.  In 1883 [[Arthur Blomfield]] restored the south chancel chapel, and in 1887 [[John Loughborough Pearson|J.&nbsp;Loughborough Pearson]] rebuilt the east wall of the chancel and reconstructed the east window.  [[Pinnacle]]s were added to the tower, or were restored, in 1904.<ref name=pev>{{Citation | last =Newman| first =John| authorlink = | last2 = Pevsner | first2 = Nikolaus | author2-link = Nikolaus Pevsner | series= The Buildings of England| title =Shropshire |edition= | publisher =[[Yale University Press]] | year =2006 | location =New Haven and London | pages = 262<U+2013>264| isbn =0-300-12083-4 }}</ref>

==Architecture==

===Exterior===
St Mary's is constructed in [[sandstone]] with [[slate]] roofs.<ref name=nhl/>  It has a [[cruciform#Cruciform architectural plan|cruciform]] plan, with a five [[bay (architecture)|bay]] nave, north and south [[aisle]]s, north and south transepts, a chancel with north and south chapels, and a tower at the [[crossing (architecture)|crossing]].  The tower is in two stages, with pairs of two-light [[Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular]] bell openings.  Above these are a [[quatrefoil]] [[frieze]], [[gargoyle]]s, a [[battlement]]ed [[parapet]], and eight pinnacles.  The transepts were originally in [[Early English Gothic|Early English]] style, and the north doorway of the north transept is still in that style.  The north chancel chapel is in Perpendicular style.<ref name=pev/>

===Interior===
The nave [[arcade (architecture)|arcades]] are carried on clustered [[pier (architecture)|piers]] and have [[molding (decorative)|moulded]] arches.  The crossing is in Early English style.  The roof of the south chancel chapel is considered to be one of the finest in the county.<ref name=pev/>  It is carried on stone [[corbel]]s, which are carved alternately with heads and foliage.  It has a low pitch, and contains moulded and carved beams, moulded [[rafter]]s, [[boss (architecture)|bosses]], and quatrefoil panels. The bosses are carved with the heraldry of the [[Earl of Derby#The Stanley Creation|Stanley]] family. The west arch of the chapel has a pierced timber [[tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]].  Between the north chancel chapel and the chancel is an arcade carried on octagonal piers.  In the chancel is a Perpendicular triple [[sedilia]].  The [[baptismal font|font]] dates from the 19th&nbsp;century and contains panels carved with depictions of [[Passion (Christianity)|Christ's Passion]]; it has replaced an earlier font of 1569.  Other items of furniture, including the [[pulpit]] and [[lectern]], were designed by Scott.<ref name=pev/>

There is stained glass in all the windows.  That in the east window, dating from 1889 is by [[Heaton, Butler and Bayne]], and depicts the [[Ascension of Jesus|Ascension]].  The east window in the south chapel, dating from 1883, is by [[Burlison and Grylls]], and depicts Christ and saints.  In the south transept and the aisles are windows from 1849<U+2013>50 by [[William Wailes]], the north window in the north transept of about 1853 is by O'Connor, and the west window of the nave, dated 1849, is by [[William Warrington]].  The oldest monument in the church dates from the early 14th&nbsp;century and consists of the recumbent figure of a knight, now mounted vertically. There is also a tombchest containing the [[alabaster]] [[effigy|effigies]] of [[Francis Kynaston (died 1590)|Sir&nbsp;Francis Kynaston]], who died in 1581, and his wife.<ref name=pev/>  The three-[[manual (music)|manual]] [[pipe organ]] was built by [[Nicholson & Co (Worcester) Ltd|Nicholson and Company]] in 1928, and later moved to the east side of the north transept.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.npor.org.uk/cgi-bin/Rsearch.cgi?Fn=Rsearch&rec_index=N01369| title = Shropshire, Ellesmere, St. Mary, Church Street (N01369)| accessdate = 14 February 2013| publisher = [[British Institute of Organ Studies]]}}</ref>  The organ was rebuilt with additions in 1997 by Cartwright and Cartwright.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.npor.org.uk/cgi-bin/Rsearch.cgi?Fn=Rsearch&rec_index=R01689| title = Shropshire, Ellesmere, St. Mary, Church Street (R01689)| accessdate = 14 February 2013| publisher = [[British Institute of Organ Studies]]}}</ref>  There is a [[ring of bells|ring]]of eight bells, all cast by [[Rudhall of Gloucester]]; three of these are dated 1727, four are dated 1768, and the eighth bell is dated 1799.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=ellesmere&Submit=+Go+&DoveID=ELLESMERE| title = Ellesmere, S Mary| accessdate = 14 February 2013| publisher = [[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]]}}</ref>

==External features==

In the churchyard is a [[sundial]] dated 1726.  It consists of a stone vase-shaped [[baluster]] standing on a two-tier base, which carries a stone basin with a bronze dial.  The sundial is listed at Grade&nbsp;II.<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1366735|desc=  Sundial to south-east of St Mary's Church in churchyard, Ellesmere Urban|accessdate= 14 February 2013|separator=,|ps=|fewer-links=x}}</ref>

